WEBVTT

1
00:00:52.160 --> 00:00:53.800
NARRATOR: <i>The war</i>
<i>between sorcerers</i>

2
00:00:53.880 --> 00:00:56.400
<i>was fought in</i>
<i>the shadows of history</i>

3
00:00:56.520 --> 00:01:01.840
<i>and the fate of mankind</i>
<i>rested with the just</i>
<i>and powerful Merlin.</i>

4
00:01:03.560 --> 00:01:07.040
<i>He taught</i>
<i>his secrets to three</i>
<i>trusted apprentices,</i>

5
00:01:07.200 --> 00:01:11.440
<i>Balthazar, Veronica,</i>
<i>and Horvath.</i>

6
00:01:12.400 --> 00:01:14.280
<i>He should have</i>
<i>trusted only two.</i>

7
00:01:22.120 --> 00:01:24.720
<i>Veronica and Balthazar</i>
<i>witnessed the savagery</i>

8
00:01:24.800 --> 00:01:27.000
<i>of a sorcerer</i>
<i>beyond evil,</i>

9
00:01:31.840 --> 00:01:36.080
<i>Morgana le Fay,</i>
<i>Merlin's most deadly enemy.</i>

10
00:01:53.120 --> 00:01:55.280
We are but servants.

11
00:01:57.280 --> 00:01:58.920
Merlin.
Horvath!

12
00:02:00.640 --> 00:02:01.920
You betray me?

13
00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:03.000
(GASPS)

14
00:02:05.160 --> 00:02:06.720
I am no one's servant.

15
00:02:09.240 --> 00:02:11.520
Well done.
Now get the spell.

16
00:02:11.640 --> 00:02:16.560
NARRATOR: <i>And so it was.</i>
<i>Morgana gained sorcery's</i>
<i>most dangerous spell</i>

17
00:02:16.800 --> 00:02:19.080
<i>known as "The Rising,"</i>

18
00:02:19.280 --> 00:02:22.280
<i>giving Morgana</i>
<i>the power to raise</i>
<i>an army of the dead</i>

19
00:02:22.360 --> 00:02:23.960
<i>and enslave mankind.</i>

20
00:02:39.480 --> 00:02:42.400
<i>Veronica sacrificed</i>
<i>herself for Balthazar</i>

21
00:02:42.480 --> 00:02:45.800
<i>by drawing Morgana's soul</i>
<i>into her own body.</i>

22
00:02:46.040 --> 00:02:49.280
<i>But Morgana</i>
<i>began to kill her</i>
<i>from the inside.</i>

23
00:02:51.520 --> 00:02:55.000
<i>To save Veronica's life</i>
<i>and to capture Morgana,</i>

24
00:02:55.160 --> 00:02:58.520
<i>Balthazar trapped them both</i>
<i>in the Grimhold,</i>

25
00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:00.680
<i>an inescapable prison.</i>

26
00:03:02.840 --> 00:03:05.800
<i>Over time, Balthazar</i>
<i>fought many sorcerers</i>

27
00:03:05.880 --> 00:03:07.520
<i>who tried to</i>
<i>free Morgana,</i>

28
00:03:07.680 --> 00:03:10.640
<i>trapping them in layer</i>
<i>upon layer of the doll.</i>

29
00:03:12.040 --> 00:03:14.880
<i>Eventually, he captured</i>
<i>Horvath as well.</i>

30
00:03:16.920 --> 00:03:20.720
<i>As Merlin lay dying,</i>
<i>he gave Balthazar</i>
<i>his dragon ring,</i>

31
00:03:20.880 --> 00:03:23.280
<i>saying it would</i>
<i>guide him to the child</i>

32
00:03:23.360 --> 00:03:26.360
<i>who would one day grow</i>
<i>to be Merlin's successor,</i>

33
00:03:26.800 --> 00:03:28.280
<i>the Prime Merlinean.</i>

34
00:03:28.560 --> 00:03:30.880
The Prime Merlinean
is the only one

35
00:03:31.760 --> 00:03:34.200
who can kill Morgana.

36
00:03:34.400 --> 00:03:37.520
NARRATOR: <i>Balthazar would</i>
<i>search for centuries.</i>

37
00:03:53.520 --> 00:03:57.080
<i>And never, it is said,</i>
<i>will Balthazar waver</i>
<i>from his quest,</i>

38
00:03:57.760 --> 00:04:00.080
<i>for mankind will</i>
<i>never be safe</i>

39
00:04:00.240 --> 00:04:05.920
<i>until Morgana is destroyed</i>
<i>by the Prime Merlinean.</i>

40
00:04:10.600 --> 00:04:12.560
(ALARM CLOCK BUZZING)

41
00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:17.760
Hey, Tank. How did you
even get up here?

42
00:04:18.040 --> 00:04:20.520
DAVE'S MOM: David?
Field trip today.

43
00:04:20.600 --> 00:04:22.800
Don't forget to wear
clean underwear.

44
00:04:22.880 --> 00:04:24.880
She means me, not you.

45
00:04:36.120 --> 00:04:38.440
(KIDS LAUGHING)

46
00:04:51.800 --> 00:04:53.800
You're not supposed
to be doing that, Dave.

47
00:04:54.920 --> 00:04:55.920
Now!

48
00:04:58.680 --> 00:04:59.680
BECKY: David.

49
00:05:01.280 --> 00:05:02.640
That's cool.

50
00:05:16.640 --> 00:05:18.760
...which means that
before Ellis Island

51
00:05:18.880 --> 00:05:21.000
and the Statue of Liberty
were built...

52
00:05:21.640 --> 00:05:23.120
DAVE: (WHISPERING)
Pass it to Becky.

53
00:05:23.280 --> 00:05:25.120
OSCAR: Pass it on.
BOY: Pass it on.

54
00:05:25.280 --> 00:05:26.600
GIRL 1:
Pass it to Becky.

55
00:05:26.720 --> 00:05:28.000
GIRL 2: Here.

56
00:05:45.840 --> 00:05:46.840
MS. ALGAR: Let's go.

57
00:05:47.040 --> 00:05:48.680
Get on the ferry.
Get your bags.

58
00:05:48.760 --> 00:05:50.400
Stay close.
Here we go.

59
00:06:00.520 --> 00:06:02.080
Hey, stop!

60
00:06:19.160 --> 00:06:20.800
Excuse me,
excuse me.

61
00:06:21.360 --> 00:06:22.560
No!

62
00:06:23.360 --> 00:06:24.400
No, lady, don't!

63
00:07:31.400 --> 00:07:32.440
No way.

64
00:07:38.960 --> 00:07:39.960
(EXCLAIMING)

65
00:07:45.680 --> 00:07:47.960
The second emperor
of the Han dynasty

66
00:07:48.120 --> 00:07:53.720
locked his
least-favorite wife in this
urn for 10 years to the day.

67
00:07:54.440 --> 00:07:58.600
They say you open it up,
the same thing will
happen to you.

68
00:07:58.800 --> 00:08:01.240
I'm sorry.
I'm looking for this note.

69
00:08:01.320 --> 00:08:04.240
Have you seen it?
It kind of just
blew into your store.

70
00:08:05.040 --> 00:08:06.160
A note?

71
00:08:06.320 --> 00:08:07.760
It blew into your store.

72
00:08:07.960 --> 00:08:09.760
(STAMMERING)
It was just a...

73
00:08:09.960 --> 00:08:11.520
Coincidence.

74
00:08:11.680 --> 00:08:13.200
Yeah, it was just
a coincidence.

75
00:08:19.280 --> 00:08:21.520
I have something
I'd like to show you, Dave.

76
00:08:21.680 --> 00:08:22.920
How'd you know
my name was Dave?

77
00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:24.400
'Cause I can read minds!

78
00:08:27.160 --> 00:08:28.560
It's on your backpack.

79
00:08:32.040 --> 00:08:33.120
Come over here.

80
00:08:47.440 --> 00:08:49.520
This is very special

81
00:08:49.680 --> 00:08:52.560
and if it likes you,
you can keep it.

82
00:08:53.880 --> 00:08:55.360
I better not.

83
00:08:55.440 --> 00:08:57.200
My teacher said
I couldn't be
gone for long.

84
00:08:57.280 --> 00:08:58.440
She knows I'm here.

85
00:08:58.560 --> 00:09:00.040
You're a bad liar, Dave.

86
00:09:01.600 --> 00:09:03.040
That's good.

87
00:09:08.880 --> 00:09:10.240
DAVE: Oh, boy.

88
00:09:37.600 --> 00:09:38.800
No way.

89
00:09:40.080 --> 00:09:44.240
I have been searching
a very long time.

90
00:09:45.800 --> 00:09:48.880
Magically, here you are.

91
00:09:49.560 --> 00:09:52.160
That ring on your finger
means something, Dave.

92
00:09:53.280 --> 00:09:54.560
It means

93
00:09:54.640 --> 00:09:58.480
you're going to be
a very important
sorcerer one day.

94
00:09:59.280 --> 00:10:04.200
And your first lesson
begins right now with
your very own Encantus.

95
00:10:05.120 --> 00:10:08.400
Do not move,
do not touch anything.

96
00:10:25.120 --> 00:10:26.480
(THUDDING)

97
00:11:08.840 --> 00:11:10.120
No way.

98
00:11:29.520 --> 00:11:30.680
When am I?

99
00:11:31.320 --> 00:11:32.680
New York City.

100
00:11:33.360 --> 00:11:36.520
Not where. The year.

101
00:11:37.480 --> 00:11:40.320
You are wasting my time.

102
00:11:45.880 --> 00:11:49.600
What happened to
"don't touch anything"?

103
00:11:49.760 --> 00:11:51.800
That's not very
sporting of you,
Balthazar.

104
00:11:51.880 --> 00:11:52.880
Be quiet.

105
00:11:53.360 --> 00:11:55.880
It's not you.
He's been like this
for 1,000 years.

106
00:11:55.960 --> 00:11:57.040
I'll explain later.

107
00:11:57.880 --> 00:11:59.960
I need the Grimhold.
Where's that doll?

108
00:12:06.280 --> 00:12:07.320
(EXCLAIMING)

109
00:12:42.720 --> 00:12:43.960
HORVATH:
I'll have that doll.

110
00:13:02.400 --> 00:13:03.480
(EXCLAIMS)

111
00:13:31.440 --> 00:13:33.440
I want that doll.

112
00:13:40.800 --> 00:13:43.240
Leave, Dave!
Leave now!

113
00:13:53.680 --> 00:13:55.400
David Stutler!
Don't ever leave your...

114
00:13:55.520 --> 00:13:57.240
There's these
crazy wizard guys
in there!

115
00:13:57.320 --> 00:13:58.520
They're made of roaches!

116
00:13:58.960 --> 00:14:02.320
No! Don't go in there!
The store's on fire!
Don't go in!

117
00:14:02.520 --> 00:14:04.160
Those guys are

118
00:14:07.480 --> 00:14:08.480
crazy.

119
00:14:12.880 --> 00:14:15.160
MS. ALGAR: You really
shouldn't tell stories.
Let's go.

120
00:14:18.160 --> 00:14:19.800
BOY 1: Ew!
He peed his pants!

121
00:14:19.920 --> 00:14:21.520
(KIDS LAUGHING)

122
00:14:22.880 --> 00:14:26.560
A jar broke.
It's just water!
There was a fire!

123
00:14:28.960 --> 00:14:31.120
BOY 1: Yeah,
Stutler had a leak.

124
00:14:31.800 --> 00:14:33.160
BOY 2:
He's such a geek.

125
00:14:58.480 --> 00:15:00.560
(BEEPING)

126
00:15:03.560 --> 00:15:05.600
Good morning.
What is that?
Oh, right.

127
00:15:07.520 --> 00:15:09.680
Good morning, beautiful.

128
00:15:13.600 --> 00:15:14.760
Hey, heads up.

129
00:15:14.880 --> 00:15:15.880
Oh.

130
00:15:15.960 --> 00:15:17.120
Happy birthday.

131
00:15:17.920 --> 00:15:19.240
Thank you, Bennet.

132
00:15:20.280 --> 00:15:21.640
You're up early.

133
00:15:22.400 --> 00:15:27.640
Professor Heiderman wants
me to give a presentation
to his Physics 101 class.

134
00:15:27.800 --> 00:15:29.920
What? Teaching long division
to English majors?

135
00:15:30.080 --> 00:15:32.880
I know.
It's like the Peace Corps,
but it's Heiderman's class.

136
00:15:32.960 --> 00:15:36.320
Hey, Bio nerds are
getting drunk tonight.

137
00:15:36.440 --> 00:15:37.440
(EXCLAIMING)

138
00:15:38.760 --> 00:15:41.400
And we invited
cheerleaders
from Princeton.

139
00:15:41.680 --> 00:15:44.080
Oh. So there's
smart cheerleaders.

140
00:15:45.240 --> 00:15:49.520
So, seriously, you're
saying you don't want to
go out on your birthday?

141
00:15:51.400 --> 00:15:54.920
I got to finish
my Tesla coil project
if I want to graduate.

142
00:15:57.320 --> 00:16:00.920
Dave, are you familiar
with the gray wolf?

143
00:16:01.080 --> 00:16:04.120
Oh, no, please, Bennet.
Not this again with
the gray wolf. I can't...

144
00:16:04.200 --> 00:16:06.640
The gray wolf
is a pack animal.

145
00:16:07.120 --> 00:16:11.440
He must find a mate.
He must hunt and grunt.

146
00:16:11.520 --> 00:16:13.280
He must participate.

147
00:16:13.440 --> 00:16:15.640
You're going to get
booted out of the pack!

148
00:16:15.800 --> 00:16:19.040
Alone. Eaten
by a hungry bear.

149
00:16:19.680 --> 00:16:22.520
That's a real
pick-me-up pep talk,

150
00:16:22.600 --> 00:16:24.800
and I'm ready
to go get the day.

151
00:16:32.520 --> 00:16:34.400
DAVE: No, no.

152
00:16:34.760 --> 00:16:36.320
Oh, man.

153
00:16:40.400 --> 00:16:42.240
Everything okay
down there?

154
00:16:42.320 --> 00:16:43.320
(STUTTERING)

155
00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:49.800
I should just
leave, right?

156
00:16:50.360 --> 00:16:51.360
Right.

157
00:17:00.880 --> 00:17:03.840
Wait. I'm sorry. Becky?

158
00:17:04.320 --> 00:17:05.760
Becky Barnes.

159
00:17:09.600 --> 00:17:11.360
Dave!

160
00:17:13.280 --> 00:17:15.000
We were in
fourth grade together.

161
00:17:15.520 --> 00:17:17.760
I do know you.
Dave Stutler.

162
00:17:17.840 --> 00:17:19.480
Right?
That's me.

163
00:17:20.480 --> 00:17:22.040
Yeah. You're that kid.

164
00:17:22.240 --> 00:17:23.640
What was that
place called?

165
00:17:23.720 --> 00:17:24.760
Arcana...

166
00:17:24.840 --> 00:17:25.880
Arcana Cabana?

167
00:17:26.200 --> 00:17:27.320
Yeah.

168
00:17:28.520 --> 00:17:30.320
So, did you transfer?

169
00:17:30.440 --> 00:17:31.480
Yeah, I did.

170
00:17:31.560 --> 00:17:35.120
And got some help.
Treatment.

171
00:17:35.400 --> 00:17:38.040
Yes, that was weird.

172
00:17:38.320 --> 00:17:42.080
You know what?
It turns out it's just
a glucose imbalance.

173
00:17:42.400 --> 00:17:43.640
Hallucinations?

174
00:17:43.760 --> 00:17:45.800
Not uncommon
in young subjects.

175
00:17:45.880 --> 00:17:47.000
Ah...

176
00:17:47.160 --> 00:17:48.320
Right.

177
00:17:48.680 --> 00:17:50.920
It's a great anecdote.

178
00:17:54.160 --> 00:17:56.160
(CLATTERING)

179
00:18:09.920 --> 00:18:11.240
DAVE: Hey, Becky.

180
00:18:12.600 --> 00:18:14.600
Becky? Hey, Becky?

181
00:18:15.160 --> 00:18:18.440
So how are you
enjoying Physics 101?

182
00:18:18.680 --> 00:18:21.640
BECKY: My brain just
does not think physics.

183
00:18:21.920 --> 00:18:23.720
So, what does
it think, then?

184
00:18:23.800 --> 00:18:25.600
Music, mostly.

185
00:18:26.440 --> 00:18:28.280
So, this is me.
(EXCLAIMING)

186
00:18:28.520 --> 00:18:30.240
You work at
the radio station?

187
00:18:30.960 --> 00:18:33.240
Yeah, I do
an afternoon show.

188
00:18:33.320 --> 00:18:35.160
Are you kidding me?
That's so cool!

189
00:18:35.240 --> 00:18:37.480
It's just
college radio.

190
00:18:37.560 --> 00:18:39.240
Like, seven people
listen to it.

191
00:18:39.760 --> 00:18:41.160
I'll be listening.
That's one more.

192
00:18:41.240 --> 00:18:42.360
You can round
it up to eight.

193
00:18:42.440 --> 00:18:43.840
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

194
00:18:45.120 --> 00:18:46.320
(SPARKING)

195
00:18:46.400 --> 00:18:48.560
I think that's
our antenna!

196
00:18:49.120 --> 00:18:50.560
What's going on?
ANDRE: Hey, gorgeous.

197
00:18:50.640 --> 00:18:54.200
The whole mixer is toast,
and Freddy called in sick.

198
00:18:54.320 --> 00:18:55.640
(DAVE CLEARING THROAT)

199
00:18:56.680 --> 00:18:58.040
Sorry to bother you.

200
00:18:58.120 --> 00:19:00.760
Where does your engineer
keep his equipment?

201
00:19:01.520 --> 00:19:02.640
Who's this guy?

202
00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:06.600
So, the good news is
you're still transmitting.

203
00:19:06.680 --> 00:19:10.200
The bad news is
your return loss,
way too high.

204
00:19:14.520 --> 00:19:16.720
All right,
if I know what I'm doing,

205
00:19:17.120 --> 00:19:21.240
we should be good!

206
00:19:21.320 --> 00:19:22.720
(SOFT MUSIC STARTS PLAYING)

207
00:19:22.800 --> 00:19:24.000
(GASPING)

208
00:19:24.080 --> 00:19:25.160
Yes!

209
00:19:26.760 --> 00:19:29.160
Thank you.
No, please,
it was my pleasure.

210
00:19:29.680 --> 00:19:32.640
I could tell
this is all pretty
important for you.

211
00:19:33.160 --> 00:19:38.000
My show is
the one thing that...
Well, you know.

212
00:19:38.080 --> 00:19:39.280
Mmm-hmm.

213
00:19:40.840 --> 00:19:43.360
Physics.
That's my thing.

214
00:19:55.480 --> 00:19:56.920
I'll see you around.

215
00:19:57.080 --> 00:19:58.880
You didn't ask her out!

216
00:19:58.960 --> 00:20:00.800
You just fixed
her antenna
and you left.

217
00:20:00.880 --> 00:20:05.200
That's not the point.
She will remember me.

218
00:20:05.440 --> 00:20:08.600
"She will remember me"?
Who are you? Braveheart?

219
00:20:08.720 --> 00:20:12.000
Bennet, I blew my shot
at getting this girl
10 years ago.

220
00:20:12.080 --> 00:20:13.720
I can't do it again.

221
00:20:14.160 --> 00:20:16.720
Now get out of here
before you get electrocuted.

222
00:20:18.320 --> 00:20:20.480
BECKY: (ON RADIO)
<i>...and it's a miracle we</i>
<i>made it on the air tonight.</i>

223
00:20:20.600 --> 00:20:23.360
<i>This show may not matter,</i>
<i>but the music does.</i>

224
00:20:23.440 --> 00:20:26.160
<i>This is Becky Barnes,</i>
<i>WNYU Radio,</i>

225
00:20:26.240 --> 00:20:27.880
<i>hoping there's music</i>
<i>all around you.</i>

226
00:20:28.080 --> 00:20:30.600
<i>(SECRETS</i> PLAYING ON RADIO)

227
00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:02.320
(CLATTERING)

228
00:21:02.400 --> 00:21:06.360
I don't understand.
Why did you have to buy
this piece of junk?

229
00:21:06.440 --> 00:21:08.800
Junk? It's an antique!

230
00:21:08.920 --> 00:21:12.120
Antique?
It's a piece of junk
from a flea market!

231
00:21:28.960 --> 00:21:30.840
Am I the first one out?

232
00:21:32.400 --> 00:21:33.640
(THUD)

233
00:21:33.720 --> 00:21:34.960
That's a yes.

234
00:21:35.160 --> 00:21:37.720
Our 10 years
are up, Balthazar.

235
00:21:38.920 --> 00:21:41.040
When I get the Grimhold
from young David,

236
00:21:41.120 --> 00:21:42.960
I'll tell him
you said hello.

237
00:21:45.200 --> 00:21:47.200
Cheerio, Balthazar!

238
00:21:54.120 --> 00:21:55.640
(GRUNTING)

239
00:22:42.880 --> 00:22:45.200
HORVATH: I thought
B- was generous.

240
00:22:45.520 --> 00:22:48.360
I've recently
been released from
a 10-year sentence,

241
00:22:48.440 --> 00:22:51.280
during which the only
reading material
available to me

242
00:22:51.440 --> 00:22:55.120
was your so-called report
on Napoleon Bonaparte

243
00:22:55.200 --> 00:22:56.880
from your school bag.

244
00:22:57.200 --> 00:22:59.160
Your analysis was obvious,
your prose was weak.

245
00:22:59.560 --> 00:23:00.800
I was nine.

246
00:23:00.880 --> 00:23:01.920
Irrelevant.

247
00:23:02.200 --> 00:23:05.720
Where's the Grimhold?
That doll you took
from the shop.

248
00:23:06.040 --> 00:23:08.680
The doll held something
very powerful.

249
00:23:08.760 --> 00:23:11.320
Something very
important to me.

250
00:23:11.600 --> 00:23:13.440
You had it last.

251
00:23:13.520 --> 00:23:14.880
I want it back.

252
00:23:14.960 --> 00:23:16.400
Listen, I'm...

253
00:23:17.320 --> 00:23:18.440
I threw it
in the street.

254
00:23:18.520 --> 00:23:19.680
Where's the Grimhold?

255
00:23:19.760 --> 00:23:21.960
It's been a long time.
I don't actually know
where it is.

256
00:23:24.800 --> 00:23:27.560
I'll cut the truth
out of you.

257
00:23:35.640 --> 00:23:36.680
Sweet.

258
00:23:37.120 --> 00:23:38.720
(ELECTRICITY CRACKLING)

259
00:23:40.000 --> 00:23:41.200
Get him.

260
00:23:41.280 --> 00:23:42.480
(GROWLING)

261
00:23:42.920 --> 00:23:45.000
Wolves? No, no, no, no.

262
00:23:53.440 --> 00:23:54.440
Oh!

263
00:23:58.600 --> 00:23:59.800
(BUZZING)

264
00:24:00.720 --> 00:24:01.720
(BEEPING)

265
00:24:01.800 --> 00:24:02.880
Thank you.

266
00:24:06.200 --> 00:24:07.360
Wolves.

267
00:24:11.800 --> 00:24:13.120
(GROWLING)

268
00:24:20.480 --> 00:24:22.960
(WHISPERING)
Man, oh, man,
oh, man, oh, man.

269
00:24:23.040 --> 00:24:24.960
(SNARLING)

270
00:24:27.280 --> 00:24:28.920
No, no, no.

271
00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:31.320
Oh, no!

272
00:24:35.280 --> 00:24:36.640
Kill him.

273
00:24:37.440 --> 00:24:38.800
No!

274
00:24:42.680 --> 00:24:43.920
Puppies?

275
00:24:50.400 --> 00:24:51.440
Oh, my.

276
00:24:54.000 --> 00:24:55.160
No way.

277
00:24:56.040 --> 00:24:57.680
Where's the doll, Dave?

278
00:24:58.840 --> 00:25:00.080
Him, him.

279
00:25:03.080 --> 00:25:04.400
(TRAIN HONKING)

280
00:25:04.520 --> 00:25:06.520
All right, get up here.
Now! Now! Hurry!

281
00:25:17.520 --> 00:25:18.520
Oh, no!

282
00:25:35.480 --> 00:25:36.480
(GASPING)

283
00:25:38.880 --> 00:25:40.560
(GROANING)

284
00:25:40.640 --> 00:25:43.360
This is not happening.
This is not happening.

285
00:25:43.440 --> 00:25:45.000
I taste sour in my mouth.

286
00:25:45.200 --> 00:25:47.360
Take it easy, Dave.
Deep breaths.

287
00:25:52.360 --> 00:25:53.360
What?

288
00:25:55.280 --> 00:25:57.120
Now that is
not happening!

289
00:25:57.240 --> 00:25:59.240
BALTHAZAR:
What's wrong?
What is it?

290
00:25:59.880 --> 00:26:01.640
No, no, no, no!

291
00:26:01.720 --> 00:26:03.800
You are not doing
this to me again!

292
00:26:04.560 --> 00:26:08.360
Do you have any idea
what my life has been like
for the last 10 years?

293
00:26:08.440 --> 00:26:10.520
I've been stuck in an urn
for the last 10 years.

294
00:26:11.480 --> 00:26:13.200
So have I!

295
00:26:13.280 --> 00:26:15.800
A figurative urn
of ridicule.

296
00:26:16.720 --> 00:26:19.800
Do you know that
in certain parts of
the tri-state area,

297
00:26:19.880 --> 00:26:22.680
they still
refer to having
a nervous breakdown

298
00:26:22.760 --> 00:26:25.960
as "pulling
a David Stutler"?
Did you know that?

299
00:26:26.080 --> 00:26:27.440
Try to be
a good listener, Dave.

300
00:26:28.920 --> 00:26:31.000
That doll is called
the Grimhold.

301
00:26:31.080 --> 00:26:34.800
It is a prison
for the most dangerous
Morganians in history,

302
00:26:35.480 --> 00:26:38.320
each one locked up
in a layer of the doll.

303
00:26:39.040 --> 00:26:43.960
Horvath wants to free
his fellow Morganians
and destroy the world.

304
00:26:45.320 --> 00:26:49.600
This must not happen.

305
00:26:50.760 --> 00:26:52.480
Yeah. For sure.

306
00:26:55.560 --> 00:26:59.800
The truth is,
you have a very
special gift.

307
00:27:01.000 --> 00:27:02.480
You need to see that.

308
00:27:02.880 --> 00:27:05.280
I just want
to be normal.

309
00:27:06.000 --> 00:27:07.080
Normal life.

310
00:27:07.160 --> 00:27:09.960
I want to forget
about that day
at Arcana Cabana.

311
00:27:10.280 --> 00:27:15.000
I want to forget about magic.
I want to forget everything.

312
00:27:17.200 --> 00:27:19.080
You should duck.
What?

313
00:27:19.960 --> 00:27:20.960
(EXCLAIMING)

314
00:27:22.280 --> 00:27:24.280
You want to
forget magic?

315
00:27:26.800 --> 00:27:28.120
Then why did you
keep the ring?

316
00:27:29.640 --> 00:27:34.160
I was going to
sell that on eBay.

317
00:27:34.360 --> 00:27:36.200
You're still
a bad liar, Dave.

318
00:27:36.280 --> 00:27:38.040
I like that about you.
It's a good sign.

319
00:27:38.640 --> 00:27:40.120
You have the gift.

320
00:27:40.240 --> 00:27:42.360
No, I have a life.

321
00:27:42.640 --> 00:27:44.920
You're the last
person Horvath saw
with the Grimhold.

322
00:27:45.000 --> 00:27:46.560
That puts you
on his list.

323
00:27:46.680 --> 00:27:50.000
So unless you want him
to turn you into a pig
who just loves physics,

324
00:27:50.280 --> 00:27:52.920
then you better help me
find that doll before
he does.

325
00:27:53.520 --> 00:27:57.040
This is crazy.
You see how crazy
this is, right?

326
00:27:57.160 --> 00:28:00.000
All right.
All right.

327
00:28:01.560 --> 00:28:04.080
You help me
get it back,
you're done.

328
00:28:04.720 --> 00:28:05.880
Really?

329
00:28:05.960 --> 00:28:07.240
You can walk away.

330
00:28:11.480 --> 00:28:13.280
Can you please
put my dresser back?

331
00:28:18.200 --> 00:28:19.880
Whoa, whoa,
whoa, whoa!

332
00:28:20.240 --> 00:28:22.160
What are you...
Oh, no.

333
00:28:22.240 --> 00:28:24.880
Please don't do that.
What are you doing?

334
00:28:25.520 --> 00:28:26.560
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

335
00:28:27.320 --> 00:28:28.320
What?

336
00:28:28.440 --> 00:28:29.760
Whoa. What is that?

337
00:28:29.840 --> 00:28:31.320
It's my Grimhold
tracking device.

338
00:28:31.760 --> 00:28:35.560
Biometric pressure spell
displaces the atmosphere
above the doll.

339
00:28:35.720 --> 00:28:37.160
Looks like downtown.

340
00:28:37.440 --> 00:28:39.760
If we can track
the Grimhold,
so can Horvath.

341
00:28:39.840 --> 00:28:41.520
So why don't we just
take the eagle?

342
00:28:41.600 --> 00:28:44.160
Too high-profile
for a trip downtown.

343
00:28:46.240 --> 00:28:47.280
I'll have to
call you a tow.

344
00:28:47.360 --> 00:28:48.400
Won't be necessary.

345
00:28:48.480 --> 00:28:50.640
Yeah, but this car's been
impounded for 10 years.

346
00:28:53.600 --> 00:28:55.400
This is low-profile.

347
00:28:55.960 --> 00:28:56.960
(ENGINE STARTING)

348
00:28:58.280 --> 00:28:59.480
She missed me.

349
00:29:04.360 --> 00:29:05.480
I'm going to give you
the basics.

350
00:29:05.560 --> 00:29:07.840
Strictly Sorcery 101.
Put on the ring.

351
00:29:07.920 --> 00:29:08.960
(STAMMERING)

352
00:29:09.280 --> 00:29:10.960
Nothing's going to happen.

353
00:29:11.080 --> 00:29:12.160
Yeah?

354
00:29:13.000 --> 00:29:14.000
(EXCLAIMING)

355
00:29:14.080 --> 00:29:15.520
(DAVE SCREAMING)

356
00:29:16.600 --> 00:29:20.440
Kidding. You've heard
how people use only
10% of their brains?

357
00:29:20.760 --> 00:29:23.600
Sorcerers can manipulate
matter because they're
born with the capability

358
00:29:23.680 --> 00:29:25.720
to use the entire power
of their brains.

359
00:29:25.840 --> 00:29:29.360
Which also explains
why molecular physics
comes so easily to you.

360
00:29:29.440 --> 00:29:32.280
So, wait. Is sorcery
science or magic?

361
00:29:32.360 --> 00:29:33.760
Yes and yes.

362
00:29:33.840 --> 00:29:36.200
For now, all you need
is a basic combat spell.

363
00:29:36.320 --> 00:29:37.320
Making fire.

364
00:29:37.800 --> 00:29:39.760
What causes molecules
to heat up?

365
00:29:39.840 --> 00:29:40.880
They vibrate.

366
00:29:40.960 --> 00:29:43.320
Everything we see
is in a constant
state of vibration,

367
00:29:43.400 --> 00:29:45.200
thus the illusion
of solidity.

368
00:29:45.280 --> 00:29:47.040
But how do we take that
which appears solid

369
00:29:47.120 --> 00:29:48.880
and have it
burst into flames?

370
00:29:48.960 --> 00:29:51.080
We will the vibrations
to go faster.

371
00:29:51.160 --> 00:29:53.360
Step one, (INHALING)
clear your mind.

372
00:29:53.440 --> 00:29:56.000
Step two,
see the molecules.

373
00:29:56.080 --> 00:29:58.400
Step three,
make them shake.

374
00:29:58.480 --> 00:29:59.480
(EXCLAIMING)

375
00:29:59.880 --> 00:30:00.880
Got it?

376
00:30:00.960 --> 00:30:02.480
No! I definitely
don't "got it."

377
00:30:02.560 --> 00:30:05.040
Trust the ring, Dave.
And keep it subtle.

378
00:30:05.640 --> 00:30:08.080
Civilians mustn't
know magic exists.

379
00:30:08.160 --> 00:30:09.600
That would be
complicated.

380
00:30:09.680 --> 00:30:13.600
Says the guy
in the 350-year-old
rawhide trench coat.

381
00:30:20.640 --> 00:30:22.360
DAVE: <i>I threw it</i>
<i>in the street.</i>

382
00:30:24.480 --> 00:30:26.640
<i>It's been a long time.</i>
<i>I don't actually know</i>
<i>where it is.</i>

383
00:30:26.720 --> 00:30:28.760
<i>I threw it</i>
<i>in the street.</i>

384
00:30:29.680 --> 00:30:30.760
<i>Don't go in there!</i>

385
00:30:30.840 --> 00:30:32.840
BOY 1: <i>Ew!</i>
<i>He peed his pants!</i>

386
00:30:32.960 --> 00:30:35.000
DAVE: <i>The store's on fire!</i>
<i>Don't go in!</i>
<i>Those guys are...</i>

387
00:30:36.000 --> 00:30:38.280
<i>It's just water!</i>
<i>There was a fire!</i>

388
00:30:40.240 --> 00:30:41.960
<i>I threw it</i>
<i>in the street.</i>

389
00:30:42.120 --> 00:30:43.440
But where?

390
00:30:43.520 --> 00:30:44.560
(KIDS CHANTING)

391
00:30:53.560 --> 00:30:54.600
(CAR HORN HONKING)

392
00:30:54.680 --> 00:30:56.720
Get out of the way, freak!
I need to pull in there!

393
00:30:56.960 --> 00:30:58.240
Are you addressing me?

394
00:30:58.400 --> 00:30:59.840
Hey, don't mess with me.

395
00:31:03.880 --> 00:31:05.240
Where was I?

396
00:31:06.720 --> 00:31:08.080
Chinatown.

397
00:31:08.520 --> 00:31:10.520
(CHEERFUL MUSIC PLAYING)

398
00:31:27.280 --> 00:31:30.600
This is it.
I'll get the Grimhold.
Keep an eye out for Horvath.

399
00:31:39.560 --> 00:31:40.680
Hi.

400
00:32:06.000 --> 00:32:09.920
Can I help you?
Do you have
an appointment?

401
00:32:10.000 --> 00:32:12.360
I'm sorry to trouble you.
I'm looking for a...

402
00:32:12.560 --> 00:32:14.080
Well, it's rather strange.

403
00:32:14.200 --> 00:32:16.440
It's a nesting doll.
It's about this big.

404
00:32:16.760 --> 00:32:18.800
Angry-looking
Chinese gentleman
on the front.

405
00:32:18.920 --> 00:32:20.960
Nesting doll?
Yes.

406
00:32:21.040 --> 00:32:23.800
It's possible.
I collect so many objects.

407
00:32:24.120 --> 00:32:25.160
(SPEAKING CANTONESE)

408
00:32:25.280 --> 00:32:26.800
YOUR HAIR IS BEAUTIFUL

409
00:32:26.960 --> 00:32:28.880
Ah!

410
00:32:29.440 --> 00:32:31.280
You speak Mandarin.

411
00:32:31.360 --> 00:32:32.600
Ah.

412
00:32:36.440 --> 00:32:38.240
That was Cantonese, Horvath.

413
00:32:39.880 --> 00:32:41.840
The Grimhold.
Where is it?

414
00:32:41.920 --> 00:32:45.360
HORVATH: An old associate
of mine speaks impeccable
Cantonese.

415
00:32:45.440 --> 00:32:47.480
He lived about
200 years ago.

416
00:32:47.600 --> 00:32:49.560
Know him? Sun Lok.

417
00:32:51.000 --> 00:32:54.480
Of course you do.
You locked him
inside the Grimhold.

418
00:32:56.480 --> 00:32:57.560
Whoops.

419
00:32:57.640 --> 00:32:59.320
Opened it.

420
00:33:06.480 --> 00:33:07.680
Whoa!

421
00:33:07.760 --> 00:33:08.800
Are you all right?

422
00:33:09.640 --> 00:33:10.640
Looks like...

423
00:33:11.320 --> 00:33:12.320
What the...

424
00:33:13.400 --> 00:33:14.440
Yay!

425
00:33:14.520 --> 00:33:16.080
I'm like one of them.

426
00:33:16.160 --> 00:33:17.200
Dave?

427
00:33:18.280 --> 00:33:19.280
You should run.

428
00:33:19.360 --> 00:33:20.800
(LAUGHS NERVOUSLY)

429
00:33:37.320 --> 00:33:38.320
(SPEAKING CANTONESE)

430
00:33:38.920 --> 00:33:41.880
THIS THING IS GETTING HEAVY

431
00:33:43.520 --> 00:33:45.480
Sorry. Sorry. I'm sorry.

432
00:33:45.560 --> 00:33:47.040
(CROWD SCREAMING)

433
00:33:47.160 --> 00:33:48.160
(ROARING)

434
00:34:18.160 --> 00:34:19.120
(GASPING)

435
00:34:19.720 --> 00:34:20.720
Be still.

436
00:34:31.160 --> 00:34:32.520
(SCREAMING)

437
00:34:39.800 --> 00:34:41.240
Balthazar!

438
00:34:48.480 --> 00:34:49.840
Oh, God. Come on.

439
00:34:52.400 --> 00:34:53.920
You skipped
the first step!

440
00:34:54.080 --> 00:34:56.040
Clear your mind!
Skipped the first step.

441
00:34:57.200 --> 00:34:58.160
(EXCLAIMING)

442
00:35:00.360 --> 00:35:01.560
(PEOPLE SCREAMING)

443
00:35:01.640 --> 00:35:04.080
Clear my mind?
Are you insane?

444
00:35:06.000 --> 00:35:07.080
Little bit.

445
00:35:19.760 --> 00:35:20.760
Oh, man.

446
00:35:29.560 --> 00:35:30.920
This is it.

447
00:35:31.800 --> 00:35:33.720
Clear your mind. Believe.

448
00:35:55.320 --> 00:35:57.200
(DAVE EXCLAIMING EXCITEDLY)

449
00:35:59.480 --> 00:36:00.480
Yeah!

450
00:36:01.840 --> 00:36:03.760
Go Team Magical Stuff!

451
00:36:09.320 --> 00:36:10.960
(DAVE EXCLAIMING)

452
00:36:13.520 --> 00:36:15.760
Did you see that?
Did you see what
I just did?

453
00:36:15.840 --> 00:36:16.840
I did it.

454
00:36:20.240 --> 00:36:21.800
(POLICE SIRENS WAILING)

455
00:36:21.880 --> 00:36:23.200
It can't be.

456
00:36:29.440 --> 00:36:30.640
Unbelievable.

457
00:36:34.600 --> 00:36:36.520
Hey, what do you got?
Did you see
what happened here?

458
00:36:36.600 --> 00:36:38.160
You know what?

459
00:36:38.240 --> 00:36:41.520
Bottle rocket meets
paper dragon in this
Asian festival.

460
00:36:41.880 --> 00:36:43.320
Lit it up like
a birthday cake.

461
00:36:43.400 --> 00:36:45.520
We got swamped with
calls saying there
was a real dragon.

462
00:36:45.680 --> 00:36:47.160
(LAUGHING)

463
00:36:47.240 --> 00:36:48.960
Between you and me, Cap,
I think some of these folks

464
00:36:49.040 --> 00:36:51.440
were hitting the sake
pretty hard.

465
00:36:51.720 --> 00:36:53.760
Sake's Japanese, actually.

466
00:36:58.480 --> 00:36:59.480
Carry on.

467
00:37:01.880 --> 00:37:03.280
"Sake's Japanese"?

468
00:37:03.360 --> 00:37:04.360
Well, it is.

469
00:37:04.440 --> 00:37:05.720
I was in character.

470
00:37:05.800 --> 00:37:06.920
Oh, right.

471
00:37:12.720 --> 00:37:14.240
You may now
return the ring to me.

472
00:37:16.680 --> 00:37:19.600
I'm a man of my word.
You helped me, we're done.

473
00:37:20.040 --> 00:37:21.480
Right. Right.

474
00:37:26.920 --> 00:37:28.680
I'd like to learn
some more.

475
00:37:31.000 --> 00:37:32.760
We'll need
a place to work.

476
00:37:34.240 --> 00:37:36.000
Somewhere under
Horvath's radar.

477
00:37:36.160 --> 00:37:37.760
I think I can
help with that.

478
00:37:46.320 --> 00:37:50.080
This was originally
a subway turnaround.

479
00:37:50.240 --> 00:37:51.720
They let me
work down here

480
00:37:51.800 --> 00:37:55.240
because some of my
experiments skew
a bit dangerous.

481
00:37:56.640 --> 00:38:00.400
Oh, my professor has
a hookup, so nobody
knows we're down here.

482
00:38:02.600 --> 00:38:04.040
Oh.

483
00:38:04.120 --> 00:38:06.760
I didn't have a chance
to give you this before.

484
00:38:07.520 --> 00:38:09.040
Your Encantus.

485
00:38:11.000 --> 00:38:13.120
I remember it
being bigger.

486
00:38:13.240 --> 00:38:14.800
Pocket edition.

487
00:38:15.240 --> 00:38:17.480
The Encantus is
our textbook.

488
00:38:17.640 --> 00:38:23.080
The art and science
and history of sorcery.

489
00:38:23.960 --> 00:38:26.000
Including our recent
history as well.

490
00:38:29.320 --> 00:38:30.360
Come on.

491
00:38:31.400 --> 00:38:34.000
See? There you are.

492
00:38:35.680 --> 00:38:36.680
Oh.

493
00:38:37.640 --> 00:38:40.360
Before we can put Horvath
back inside the Grimhold,

494
00:38:40.480 --> 00:38:43.160
we must first turn you
into a sorcerer,

495
00:38:43.880 --> 00:38:45.480
which begins now.

496
00:38:45.880 --> 00:38:47.240
Step back.

497
00:38:48.640 --> 00:38:49.800
I really was
doing stuff.

498
00:38:49.880 --> 00:38:51.080
Eyes open.

499
00:38:51.160 --> 00:38:52.640
Mouth closed.

500
00:39:03.160 --> 00:39:04.240
(EXCLAIMS)

501
00:39:26.440 --> 00:39:28.360
This is the Merlin Circle.

502
00:39:29.200 --> 00:39:30.720
